      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the comfortable end of your easy range. Let your body settle in — no need to rush.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":48,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic effort. Conversational pace throughout — you should be able to speak in full sentences.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace for the final few minutes. Notice how you feel — this data is useful coaching feedback.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at an easy, relaxed jog. No GPS-chasing today — just get the legs moving comfortably.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 2–3 minutes post-run and do a light hamstring and calf stretch, paying gentle attention to that left Achilles.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the aerobic foundation for the week. With a VDOT of 46.7 and a maintenance goal, we want to preserve the aerobic base you've built without adding unnecessary stress. This run stays fully in your easy zone (5:22–5:56 /km) — the physiological purpose here is capillary development and mitochondrial density, not fitness gains per se, but fitness preservation. Given your Achilles history, the easy pace also minimizes tendon load on a fresh-week day.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Cruise Interval Tempo\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":62,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":336,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"A genuine 15-minute warmup is non-negotiable for threshold work. Easy and relaxed — this primes the cardiovascular and neuromuscular systems.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"3 x 8 minutes at threshold pace (4:28 /km). This is comfortably hard — you can speak a few words but not a full sentence. Take 90 seconds of easy jogging between each rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":2,\"notes\":\"90-second to 2-minute easy jog between cruise intervals. Keep moving — don't stop completely.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy to flush lactate and bring heart rate down gently.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes at easy pace (5:22–5:36 /km). Include 4–6 light strides of 20 seconds in the final 2 minutes if you feel loose enough.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jog, then 5 minutes of dynamic stretching. Focus on calf raises (slow and controlled) as Achilles maintenance — both legs.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals — threshold-pace efforts with short recoveries — are the most efficient tool for maintaining lactate threshold fitness. At your level, 3 x 8 minutes at 4:28 /km delivers a meaningful stimulus without the recovery debt of longer tempo runs. Physiologically, this keeps your lactate turn-point honest so that your marathon pace (4:43 /km) continues to feel manageable. This is the week's primary quality session — the rest of the week is designed to support it.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — at or slower than 5:56 /km if needed. Wednesday after a Tuesday tempo is not the day to push. The physiological work happens here through active recovery, not additional stress.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the entire run IS the warmup pace. Start slowly and only pick up slightly if your body invites it.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"A short walk and gentle stretch. No need for anything elaborate — preservation is the goal today.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is a deliberate recovery run — shorter and slower than your easy runs on other days. After Tuesday's threshold work, your body is processing adaptation. Running easy on Wednesday accelerates blood flow and clears metabolic waste without adding meaningful training stress. The temptation to make this feel 'productive' by running faster is worth resisting — the adaptation from Tuesday happens most fully when Wednesday stays truly easy.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":68,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":336,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy. Include 4 x 20-second pickups near the end to prime your neuromuscular system before the intervals.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 5 minutes at interval pace (4:11 /km). This is hard — near your 10K effort. You're working, but you're not sprinting. Equal recovery (5 minutes easy jog) between each.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"5 minutes of easy jogging between each interval. Full recovery is intentional — the goal is to hit pace on every rep, not to accumulate fatigue.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":13,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"10–15 minutes easy to bring the system down gently. This is non-optional after VO2max work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy with 4 x 20-second strides. Start the strides at moderate effort and build to interval effort — prime the engine before you open it up.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Minimum 10 minutes easy jog, then calf stretches and left Achilles attention. Consider a 5-minute walk after the jog if you feel particularly worked.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the second quality session of the week and the most physiologically demanding. At 4:11 /km, you're working at or near your maximal oxygen uptake, which is a powerful stimulus for maintaining aerobic capacity. For maintenance, the goal isn't to push this volume higher — it's to keep the ceiling from dropping. Five reps of 5 minutes is a solid, evidence-based dose. If any rep feels like it's falling apart, it's okay to stop at 4 — quality over quantity always.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":336,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease into the run — your legs may have some residual fatigue from Thursday's intervals.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":43,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy aerobic running at 5:22–5:36 /km. Relaxed, smooth, and controlled.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":1,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":236,\"intensity\":\"Repetition\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second strides near the end of the run. Quick, light turnover — not a sprint. Full recovery (60–90 seconds walk/jog) between each.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy cool-down jog to close out. You're setting up Saturday's rest and Sunday's long run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start easy — this run follows a hard interval day. No pressure to hit the top of the easy range early.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Light stretching. Gentle calf raises as Achilles maintenance. If any Achilles tenderness is present, skip the strides today and flag it.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's run is easy with a small neuromuscular bonus: 4 short strides. Strides at near-repetition pace (around 3:56 /km effort for 20 seconds) keep your fast-twitch recruitment sharp without meaningful fatigue cost. They also improve running economy, which translates directly to more efficient marathon-pace running. The run itself stays easy to preserve freshness for Sunday's long run — Saturday is a full rest day for the same reason.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery — Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"40 minutes of low-impact cross-training: cycling, swimming, yoga, or light mobility work. Keep effort genuinely easy — HR should stay well below aerobic threshold. This is active recovery, not a training stimulus.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — ease into whatever modality you choose at a very comfortable effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5–10 minutes of gentle mobility or stretching. A focus on hip flexors, calves, and Achilles tissue health is a good use of this time.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is a deliberate buffer between Friday's run and Sunday's long run. Optional low-impact cross-training — cycling, swimming, or yoga — maintains blood flow and mobility without adding running stress. Given your Achilles history, this is also a good day for targeted mobility work around the lower leg. If life is full on Saturdays, complete rest is equally valid. The goal is to arrive at Sunday's long run feeling ready, not depleted.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":115,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":336,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":283,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes at the relaxed end of easy pace. Let your body settle — long run pace should feel sustainable from the very first kilometer.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":85,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":336,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"The bulk of the run at easy aerobic pace (5:22–5:36 /km). Resist the urge to push — the long run's value comes from time on feet and fat oxidation, not pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":283,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional: final 4 km at marathon pace (4:43 /km) if you feel genuinely strong. If not, continue at easy pace. This is a feel-based decision, not an obligation.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":0,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 3–5 minutes. Rehydrate immediately. Your long run fueling during the run (every 45 minutes) matters — plan for it.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start conservatively — the first 2 km should feel almost too easy. This pays dividends in the final 5 km.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes, then a full lower-body stretch routine. Prioritize left Achilles and both calves. Refuel within 30–45 minutes of finishing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the cornerstone of your week and the most important session for maintaining your aerobic base. At 20 km, this is consistent with your recent training history and sits within your established long run range. The easy pace (5:22–5:36 /km) keeps this fully aerobic — the physiological value is in fat metabolism, cardiac stroke volume development, and musculoskeletal resilience. The optional marathon-pace finish (last 4 km at 4:43 /km) is a tool for keeping marathon-specific fitness alive without a dedicated race-pace session. It's genuinely optional — use feel, not obligation, to decide. Given your max 120-minute preference and your Achilles history, 20 km at easy pace sits comfortably within both constraints.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
